1. Kd5! { This is the only move that wins -- it makes the most progress both towards the pawns and up the board into Black's territory. } { [%csl Yf7,Yg6,Yg4,Yf4,Gd7][%cal Bc4d5,Gd5c6,Gd5d6,Gd5e6] } (1. Kd4 { Progressing towards the pawns but not into Black's half. } { [%csl Yf7,Yg6,Yf4,Yg4][%cal Bc4d4] } 1... Kf6 (1... Kf8 { Also holds the draw although it's less active. }) 2. Kd5 { [%cal Gd4d5] } 2... Ke7 3. Kc6 Ke6 { And with the opposition Black will prevent White from making further progress. White cannot use g5 as a reserve tempo to win the opposition because the simple Kf5 wins both pawns. In fact, the tablebase shows that White is now the one fighting for a draw, and only Kc5 holds! } { [%cal Gg4g5] } 4. g5 Kf5) (1. Kc5 { Progressing into Black's half of the board but not towards the kingside pawns. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gc4c5,Gg7f6,Gc5d6] } 1... Kh6 (1... Kf6 2. Kd6 { [%csl Gd6,Gf6] }) 2. Kd6 { [%cal Gc5d6] } 2... f5 3. gxf5 gxf5 4. Ke6 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge6f5] } 4... Kg6 5. Ke5 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gf4g5] } 5... Kg7! 6. Kxf5 Kf7 $22 $10 { Because White's pawn is still in his half of the board he will fail to reach a key square if Black defends properly. } { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Bg6] }) 1... Kf6 (1... Kf8 2. Kd6 Ke8 3. f5 Kf8 4. f6 Ke8 5. Kc7 { [%csl Gf6,Re7][%cal Gc7d8,Gc7d7,Gd7e7,Rf6e7] } 5... Kf8 6. Kd8 Kg8 7. Ke8 { [%csl Gg6] } (7. g5 Kf8 8. Kd7 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf8f7] })) (1... Kh6 2. Ke5 Kg7 (2... g5 3. f5 Kg7 4. Kd6 Kf6 5. Kd7 { [%csl Gf4,Gg5] } 5... Ke5 6. Ke7 Kf4 7. Kxf7 Kxg4 { [%cal Gf7e6,Gf5f6] } 8. Ke6 Kh4 9. f6 g4 10. f7 g3 11. f8=Q g2) 3. Kd6) 2. Kd6 { Again, an only move -- we need to take the opposition and infiltrate further into Black's territory. } { [%csl Gd6,Gf6][%cal Gd5d6,Gc4c5,Gc5d6] } 2... Kg7 { [%cal Gd6d7] } 3. Ke7 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Re7f7,Gf4f5] } (3. Kd7 { This is a faster win according to the tablebase but as a human I wouldn't care to allow Kf6 unless I had to. } 3... Kf6 4. Kd8! (4. Ke8 { But not this, as Ke6 leaves White with the opposition. } { [%cal Gd7e8] } 4... Ke6 5. Kf8 Kf6 $10 { [%cal Gg4g5] } 6. g5+ Ke6 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge6f7] } 7. Kg7 Ke7 { [%csl Ge7,Gg7][%cal Ge7f7] }) 4... Ke6 5. Ke8) 3... Kg8 4. Kd8 (4. f5 gxf5 5. gxf5 Kg7 { [%cal Gf5f6] } 6. f6+ (6. Kd7 Kf6 7. Ke8) 6... Kg6 $22 $19 { The trébuchet -- a case of mutual zugzwang! Whichever player has the move loses their pawn. } { [%csl Ge7,Gg6] } (6... Kg8 7. Ke8 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf6g7] })) (4. Kf6 Kf8 { [%csl Gf8,Gf6][%cal Gf8e7] } 5. f5 gxf5 6. gxf5 Ke8 7. Kg7 Ke7 { White isn't making progress. f6 is met by Ke6 with another trébuchet. } { [%cal Gf5f6,Ge7e6] } 8. f6+ Ke6) 4... Kh7 (4... f5 { [%cal Gg4f5,Gg6f5] } 5. g5 { [%csl Gf5,Gg6,Gg5,Gf4] } (5. gxf5 gxf5 6. Ke7 Kg7 7. Ke6 Kg6 8. Ke5 Kg7) 5... Kf8 6. Kd7 Kf7 7. Kd6 $22 { Black cannot maintain the opposition because White's pawn on g5 controls f6. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Gf7f6,Rg5f6] } 7... Kf8 8. Ke6 Kg7 9. Ke7 { [%cal Ge7f6] } 9... Kg8 (9... Kh7 10. Kf7 { [%csl Gh6,Gg6,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gh7h6,Rg5h6] }) 10. Kf6 $18) (4... Kg7 5. Ke8 Kf6 6. Kf8 Ke6 7. g5 { [%csl Gf7] } 7... Kf5 (7... f6 8. Kg7 (8. gxf6 Kxf6 { [%cal Gf6f5,Gg6g5] }) 8... fxg5 9. fxg5 { [%csl Gg6,Gg8,Gg5] } 9... Kf5 (9... Ke7 10. Kxg6 { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gf8g8] }) 10. Kh6) 8. Kxf7 Kxf4 9. Kxg6 $18) 5. Kd7 { [%csl Gd7,Gh7,Be7,Bf7,Bg7][%cal Gh7g8,Gd7e8] } 5... Kg7 (5... Kg8 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 6. f5 { [%cal Gg8f8,Gd7d8] }) 6. Ke8 Kg8 { [%csl Ge8,Gg8] } (6... Kf6 { As mentioned, this is slower than 3. Kd7 but now we can simply play 7. Kf8 without any headaches. } 7. Kf8 Ke6 8. g5 Kf5 9. Kxf7 Kxf4 10. Kxg6 $18 { The same position as in the 4. ... Kg7 line. }) 7. f5! { Although 4. f5 led to a draw, this move wins for White if the kings are in opposition. We'll see why. } 7... Kg7 { [%csl Gf5,Gg6][%cal Gf5g6] } (7... gxf5 { Whether Black inserts this capture now or later doesn't matter. Considering that White never wants to take on g6, Black should leave the pawn tension and afford White the opportunity to blunder. } 8. gxf5 Kg7 9. Ke7) 8. Ke7 { [%csl Ge7,Gg7] } (8. fxg6?? Kxg6 { Now Black can exchange the last pawns with f5 or just play Kg5. } { [%cal Gg6g5] }) 8... g5 { Probably one of Black's better tries. } (8... Kg8 9. f6 $22 { With a similar idea as in one of the earlier variations: Black is getting zugzwang'd out of his pawns. } { [%csl Rg7,Rf8][%cal Rf6g7,Re7f8] }) (8... gxf5 9. gxf5 { This is no help, f6 is still coming. } 9... Kg8 (9... f6 10. Ke6 { [%csl Gg6,Gf7][%cal Gf5g6,Ge6f7] } 10... Kg8 11. Kxf6 Kf8 12. Ke6 Ke8 13. f6 Kf8 14. f7 Kg7 15. Ke7) 10. f6 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge7f7] }) (8... f6 { [%cal Gg4g5] } 9. Ke6 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge6f6] } 9... g5 (9... gxf5 10. gxf5 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge6f6] }) 10. Ke7 { [%csl Gf7,Gg6][%cal Gf5g6,Ge7f7] }) 9. Ke8 { [%cal Gg7g8] } (9. f6+ Kg6 { [%csl Gf6,Gf7,Gg6,Ge7] }) 9... Kf6 (9... Kg8 10. f6 $22 { Once again Black loses his pawn. } { [%csl Rf8,Rg7][%cal Re8f8,Rf6g7] } 10... Kh7 11. Kxf7 Kh8 { [%cal Gf7e8,Gf6f7,Gf7f8] }) 10. Kf8 $22 { Again Black loses his pawn, although here White needs to realize he'll win the race. } 10... Ke5 11. Kxf7 Kf4 12. Kg6 Kxg4 13. f6 Kh4 14. f7 g4 15. f8=Q g3 $18 *


