1. e4 d5 { Our Hero supports #TeamScandi! } 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 { The most common reply, but black usually gets a solid position in this line. Instead, 3. Nf3 with the idea of establishing a d4/c4 pawn duo can be more challenging for black to handle because it denies him the d5 square. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rc3d5] } (3. Nf3 { [%csl Yd4,Yc4,Bd5][%cal Bb1c3,Yc2c4,Yd2d4,Bc4d5,Ge7e6,Gc7c6] }) 3... Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 { [%cal Gg1f3,Gf1c4] } 5. Bd3!? { An uncommon move at the master level. White usually plays 5. Nf3 or 5. Bc4. } (5. Bc4 { [%cal Ba2g8] } 5... c6 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Ne5+ { [%csl Rg4,Rf7][%cal Re5f7,Re5g4] } 8... Ke8 9. Nxg4 { [%cal Rd1g4] }) 5... c6 $140 { Qxd4 } { [%csl Yd5,Rd4][%cal Rd8d4] } (5... Qxd4?? 6. Bb5+! { [%csl Re8,Rd4][%cal Rb5e8,Rd1d4,Gd4d7] }) 6. Nge2 { [%cal Be2d4] } 6... Bg4!? 7. f3 { [%cal Bd4g1,Bh4e1] } 7... Bh5 { [%csl Yf3][%cal Yh5f3,Bg2f3,Ge2g3,Gh5g6] } 8. Bf4 { [%cal Bf4b8] } 8... e6 { [%csl Gc6,Ge6][%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e7,Gf8d6,Gd7b6,Gb6d5] } 9. Bg5 { Bf4-g5 doesn't make much sense because white could have played 8. Bg5 and thus saved a tempo. } { [%csl Rd8,Rf6][%cal Yc1f4,Yf4g5,Rg5d8] } 9... Be7 { Breaking the pin. } 10. Qd2 { [%csl Bg5,Bd2,Yh6][%cal Yg5h6] } 10... Nbd7 11. g4 { [%csl Gf3,Gg4][%cal Ge1c1] } 11... Bg6 { [%csl Bf7,Ye6][%cal Gd3c4,Bc4f7] } 12. Bxg6 (12. h4 { [%csl Gc6,Yg4,Yf3][%cal Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Ge8c8] } 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3) 12... hxg6 { [%cal Bh8h2] } 13. O-O-O { [%cal Gg2g4,Gb7b5] } 13... Qa5 14. Qf4 { [%csl Yc1,Yf4] } 14... O-O-O { [%cal Gb7b5] } (14... Nh5! { [%csl Rf4,Rg5,Yc1][%cal Re7g5,Rh5f4,Ra5g5] } 15. gxh5 (15. Qd2 Bxg5 { [%csl Rc1,Rd2][%cal Rg5c1] } 16. f4 { [%csl Rg5,Rh5] } 16... Nxf4 17. Nxf4 Rh3 $140 { Rf3 } { [%csl Bh3,Rf4,Rd2,Rc1][%cal Bf4h3,Rg5c1,Yh3f3,Rf3f4] } 18. Rhf1 Nb6 $140 { Nc4 } { [%csl Rd2,Rf1,Rd1,Rc1,Rf4][%cal Rb6c4,Rc4d2,Gc4e3,Re3f1,Re3d1,Rg5c1] }) 15... Bxg5 { [%csl Rc1,Rf4][%cal Rg5c1,Ba5g5] }) 15. Ng3 Nb6 { [%cal Gh2h4,Gc1b1] } (15... Nh5! { With similar lines as before. } { [%csl Rg5,Yc1,Yf4][%c