1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 { Perfectly playable, although 2. Nf3 is more normal. } { [%cal Gd7d5,Gd5d4] } (2. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gd2d4,Gc2c3] }) 2... Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 { We've now transposed into a very common position. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge7c5] } 5. Ng5 { An unusual move. Trading two pieces for pawn and rook is very rarely a good idea. } { [%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] } 5... O-O { [%csl Gc4,Gg5,Gf7,Gf8] } 6. d3 { [%cal Gg5f7] } 6... d6 7. O-O Bg4 { [%cal Gd1e1,Gf2f4] } 8. f3!? { Weakening the dark squares but preserving a tempo. } { [%cal Bb6g1,Bh4e1,Gc1h6] } (8. Qe1 Nd4 { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gd4c2] }) (8. Nf3 Nd4 { [%csl Gf3] }) 8... Bh5!? { Although counter-intuitive, Bd7 might have been preferable to discourage Nh3. } { [%csl Gf8][%cal Gh5f7] } (8... Bd7 { [%cal Gd7h3,Gh7h6] } 9. Be3 h6 10. Nxf7 Rxf7 11. P@g6 { [%cal Gc4g8] }) 9. Nh3 { Re-routing the knight, which makes sense given that the Bh5 overprotects f7. } { [%cal Gh3f2,Gh5d1,Gf2h1,Gh1g3] } 9... Na5 { Nd4 was probably better, because the Bc4 is not an especially dangerous piece. } { [%csl Gc4,Gh3,Gf3] } (9... Nd4 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc4g8,Gh5f7,Gf8f7,Gg8f7] } 10. Ne2 (10. Be3 c5 11. Bxd4 cxd4 { [%cal Bd4g1,Bh4e1,Bh6c1] }) 10... Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 N@d4 { [%cal Gc2c3] }) 10. Bb3 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gd3c4] } 10... c6 { [%csl Bc6][%cal Ga5c6,Gc6d4] } 11. Bd2 { [%cal Gd1e1,Gf3f4] } 11... a6 { c6 and a6 don't help black much and potentially weaken the dark squares. Black was probably struggling to find a plan. } { [%csl Gc6,Ga5,Gb3,Gc3][%cal Ba5d8,Ga6b5,Gc6b5] } 12. Ne2 { [%csl Gg3] } 12... Nxb3 { This exchange makes sense now, because the Na5 has been deprived of the c6 square. } 13. axb3 { [%cal Ga5d8,Ga1a5] } 13... B@e6 { [%cal Gd6d5,Gh3g5,Gh3f2] } 14. Ng3?! { Nf2 in order to preserve the pawn structure might have been better. } 14... Bxh3 15. gxh3 { [%csl Bh2,Bh3][%cal Gg3h5] } 15... Bg6 { [%csl Gf5] } (15... b5 16. Nxh5 Nxh5 { [%csl Gf4,Ge2][%cal Ge7h4,Gf4h3,Gf4g2,Ge2d1,Ge2f1] }) 16. Bg5 { I would have played N@f5 instead of Bg5, because the Bd2 was white's only defender of the dark squares. } { [%cal Ba7g1,Bh4e1,Bh6c1] } (16. N@f5 { [%csl Gf5,Gg5][%cal Gf5e7] } 16... Bxf5 17. Nxf5 { [%csl Gh6] }) 16... Nxe4? { Tactically unsound because of the coming sequence. } 17. Bxe7 { [%csl Rd8] } 17... Nxg3?? { Surely intentional and probably calculated since 16. Nxe4, but very dubious all the same. } (17... Qxe7 18. fxe4 { And black has lost a piece. Instead he opts for a dubious queen sacrifice. } { [%csl Gf5] }) (17... P@f2+ 18. Kh1 { [%cal Ge4g3,Gd8e7] } (18. Kg2 N@f4+ { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2h1,Ge4g3,Gd8e7] }) (18. Rxf2 Nxf2 19. Bxd8 Nxd1)) 18. Bxd8 N@e2+?! { p@e2 would have given better attacking chances. } (18... P@e2 { [%cal Ge2f1,Ge2d1] } 19. hxg3 exd1=Q 20. Raxd1 N@e2+) 19. Kf2 { Best, as Kg2 allows black to add another attacker with tempo. } (19. Kg2 N@f4+) 19... Nxf1 { This is a critical position in which white needs to play carefully. } { [%csl Ge2,Gf1,Gd8] } 20. Qxe2? { This allows R@d2. Qxf1 was better. } (20. Qxf1 { And black has no useful checks. } { [%csl Re2] } 20... P@e3+ { [%cal Gf2e3] } (20... Nf4 21. B@f6 R@e2+ 22. Qxe2 Nxe2 23. N@h6+ Kh8 24. Bxg7+ Kxg7 25. B@f6+ Kxh6 26. Q@g5#)) (20. Kxf1 { [%csl Ge3] } 20... N@e3+ { [%cal Ge3d1,Ge3f1] } (20... R@g1+ { [%cal Gg1d1] })) 20... P@e3+ (20... R@d2 { [%cal Rd2f2] }) 21. Kxf1 R@f2+ 22. Qxf2 exf2 { A good practical try, but white has a strong reply here. } 23. Kxf2?? (23. N@e7+ { [%cal Gg8h8] } 23... Kh8 24. R@g8+ (24. Nxg6+ hxg6 (24... fxg6 25. R@g8+ Kxg8 26. N@e7+ Kf7 (26... Kh8 27. Q@g8+ Rxg8 28. N@f7#) 27. N@g5+ (27. B@e6+ Kxe6 28. N@g5+ Kd7 29. B@e6+) 27... Ke8 { [%cal Ge8d7] }) 25. R@h7+ Kg8 (25... Kxh7 26. N@g5+ Kh6 27. Q@h7#) 26. Q@h8#) 24... Rxg8 25. Nxg6+ fxg6 (25... hxg6 26. Q@h7+!! Kxh7 27. N@g5+ Kh6 (27... Kh8 28. Nxf7+ Kh7 29. N@g5#) 28. Nxf7+ Kh5 (28... Kh7 29. N@g5#) 29. P@g4#) 26. N@f7#) 23... Rfxd8 24. N@e7+ Kh8?? $18 { [%cal Ge7g6] } (24... Kf8 $7 25. Nxg6+ (25. N@e6+ fxe6 (25... Kxe7 26. B@f8+ Rxf8 27. R@d7+ Kxd7 28. Q@c7+ K